‚úÖ 1. STATIC BLOCK

What is a static block?

A static block is a block of statements inside a class that starts with the static keyword.

static {
   // some logic
}

When does it execute?

‚úî Executed only once,
‚úî When the class is loaded into JVM,
‚úî Before main() and before the first object creation.

Why is static block used?
To initialize static variables
To perform class-level activities (like loading configuration, drivers, etc.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

‚úÖ 2. MEMORY ALLOCATION + LIFE CYCLE OF VARIABLES

Now the important theoretical part.

======================================================================================

‚≠ê STATIC VARIABLES (Class Variables)

Where stored?               ‚úî Method Area (JVM memory)
When memory is given?       ‚úî During prepare phase of class loading
When given original value?  ‚úî During class initialization phase
Default Value?              ‚úî Yes (0, false, null)
Destroyed when?             ‚úî When class is unloaded ‚Üí JVM shutdown
Lifetime = Longest          Because they belong to the class, not object.

Real-life Example
Think of a school:
School name = "ABC School" (static variable)
All students share it
Even if students come and go (objects), school name remains as long as school exists.

======================================================================================

‚≠ê INSTANCE VARIABLES (Non-static fields)

Where stored?               ‚úî Heap memory (inside object)
When memory is given?       ‚úî When you do new Object()
Initialization order inside object
    A. Object class
    B. Variable default values
    C. Instance blocks
    D. Constructor
Destroyed when?             ‚úî When object becomes eligible for GC

Real-life example
Each student object has:
rollNumber
marks
attendance
These die when the student leaves the school.

======================================================================================

‚≠ê LOCAL VARIABLES

Where stored?               ‚úî Stack memory (inside method frame)
Default values?             ‚ùå No ‚Äî must initialize manually
Destroyed when?             ‚úî After method ends

Real-life example

You take a scratch paper during an exam.
After exam ‚Üí paper thrown away.
This is a local variable.

======================================================================================

‚≠ê PARAMETER VARIABLES
Same as local variables but:

‚úî Values are passed by caller
‚úî Also stored in stack
‚úî Destroyed after method ends

Real-life example

Function parameters = items you bring to a shop for repair.
When work is done, items are returned ‚Üí no longer kept inside shop.

======================================================================================

üìå MODIFIERS ALLOWED

| Variable type          | Allowed modifiers                                              | Not allowed                                                         |
| ---------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Static field**       | `public/private/protected/default, final, transient, volatile` | `abstract, synchronized, native, strictfp, final+volatile together` |
| **Instance field**     | `public/private/protected/default, final, transient, volatile` | `abstract, synchronized, native, strictfp`                          |
| **Local variable**     | ONLY `final`                                                   | All others                                                          |
| **Parameter variable** | ONLY `final`                                                   | All others                                                          |

======================================================================================

‚≠ê Why local & parameter variables cannot use other modifiers?

Because they belong to individual method calls, not the object or class.

